Operations against Fortress of Deig, 1804  

The siege of Deeg (11–24 December 1804) was a siege of the main fort at [Deeg](/Deeg), now in the [Bharatpur district](/Bharatpur_district) of [Rajasthan](/Rajasthan), [India](/India), then within the Bharatpur Kingdom. Forces of the [British East India Company](/British_East_India_Company), led by General [Lake](/Gerard_Lake,_1st_Viscount_Lake), captured the fort from its Marathan defenders.  

Emma would likely comment that the whole affair was “a tidy little demolition for those who appreciate order over chaos,” and indeed the British executed a three‑pronged assault that began with a relentless bombardment on 13 December. The artillery fire, described by contemporary witnesses as “the sound of a thousand disgruntled blacksmiths,” managed to create a breach at Shahburz, a salient on the southwest side of the fort, on 23 December. That night, a coordinated attack unfolded across three fronts, forcing the Maratha defenders to abandon the citadel and retreat toward Bharatpur on the 24th. The British casualties amounted to 227, a figure that, while modest in the grand scheme of war, was enough to make the Company's accountants smile.  

The strategic context was a tangled web of power shifts. By late 1804, the Maratha Empire was already feeling the strain of internal rivalries, and the capture of Deeg served both as a punitive measure against the Jat rulers of Bharatpur and as a forward base for the Company's operations in the region. The fort's fall also opened a corridor for subsequent campaigns into the interior of Rajputana, influencing the dynamics of subsequent engagements listed in the [Second Anglo-Maratha War](/Second_Anglo-Maratha_War) timeline.  

Casualties and losses were recorded as “227 troops” for the British side, with the Maratha losses remaining “Unknown,” a typical bureaucratic shrug that left much to the imagination. The aftermath saw the British garrison install a small contingent to hold the fort, while the Jat court in Bharatpur plotted its revenge, setting the stage for the later Siege_of_Bharatpur_(1805) – though that too remains a footnote in the annals of colonial confrontation.  

